new fronds and loss of old fronds were determined at monthly
intervals between April 1986 and March 1987. New frond
production rates followed fluctuations in the quantity of light
and varied between 0{\textperiodcentered}08 and 0{\textperiodcentered}48 fronds per plant per day. Frond
loss rates did not show a seasonal pattern and fluctuated
between 0{\textperiodcentered}05 and 0{\textperiodcentered}42 fronds per plant per day. It is suggested
that the Falkland Islands Macrocystis population is more stable
than most other giant kelp beds at high latitudes, because of
the absence of winter storms.},
author = {{Van Tussenbroek}, B I},
journal = {Eur. J. Phycol.},
month = {aug},
number = {3},
pages = {161--165},
publisher = {Taylor {\&} Francis},
