@article{Odonoghue,
abstract = {Introduction South Africa is the custodian of a marine and coastal environ-ment that is remarkable for its beauty, biotic diversity, and geomorphological features. By its very nature, the coast contrib-utes substantially to the economy of the country, primarily through the fertile adjacent farmlands, its cities, ports and holiday resorts, as well as through the harvesting of marine resources and products. It is estimated that at least 35{\%} of South Africa's gross domestic product is generated in the coastal regions. 1 Recent years have seen an influx of people to the coast, and current estimates are that one-third of the population resides within 60 km of the seashore. 1 This places environmental pressure on the coastal systems, inevitably increasing the threat of their degradation, including that relating to pollution. The implementation of management procedures necessary to reduce the effects of pollution should be based on sound scientific principles. The primary objective of the study reported here was to assess the scientific basis for marine pollution monitoring in South Africa, and thereby to decide whether research on the ecological effects of marine pollution is adequate and appropriate. Pollution-monitoring projects currently being undertaken in South Africa are extremely diverse in their objectives and practice. By far the majority are linked to impact assessment studies by local authorities (municipalities) or private consul-tants, to meet town and regional planning requirements. Other consultancies concern local industries, or port authorities, in order to meet state requirements, or international protocols, such as the London Convention. 2 These types of projects are often narrowly focused. In considering immediate issues using standard procedures, their contextual frameworks limit inter-pretation of data, and their objectives contribute little to the development of scientific and technological knowledge. Globally, pollution studies have 