microhabitat relationships. The morphological forms that we
recognize are multivariate, and thus all of the attributes need
to be considered. In particular, volume (or surface area:volume
ratio) is usually a very good discriminator between groups,
indicating that both size and shape are important for defining
the groups. We recognize two main phenotypically distinct
groups, comprising plants from sheltered estuarine situations
