biochemical compounds showed that localities with low slopes
(i.e. sheltered beaches) were related to high concentrations of
lipids, proteins and carbohydrates and vice versa. The three
biochemical classes showed different trends with time and changes
were more pronounced in the sheltered beach than in the exposed
one. These results could be explained by the influence of
allochthonous inputs in the sheltered beach, which were not
observed in the exposed one. {\textcopyright} 2003 Elsevier Ltd. All rights
