relating atmospheric physics to fish production remain
unexplained. Two atmospheric conditions induce different types
of upwelling in these ecosystems: coastal, alongshore wind
stress, resulting in rapid upwelling (with high vertical
velocity, w); and wind-stress curl, resulting in slower
upwelling (low w). We show that the level of wind-stress curl
has increased and that production of Pacific sardine (Sardinops
