sporophytes live long, form extensive surface canopies that shade
the substratum and dampen currents, and produce and retain
copious amounts of reproductive propagules. The majority of
subtidal Macrocystis populations worldwide, however, are small,
narrow, fringing forests that are productive and modify
environmental resources (e.g., light), yet are more dynamic than
their large southern California counterparts with local
recruitment probably resulting from remote propagule production.
When intertidal, Macrocystis populations exhibit vegetative
