that the bending of blades, and hence canopy height, was very
sensitive to current magnitude and directly influenced current
profile. Identifying canopy height is a major factor in defining
spatial distribution of grass biomass from optical or acoustic
remote sensing devices. The model has direct implications for
biological issues related to the plants themselves and to their
associated organisms, such as the vertical distribution of
photosynthesis within the canopy and the effect of current shear
on recruitment of organisms on the blades. It can also be used
to study how eelgrass canopies affect horizontal transport of
constituents, such as dissolved oxygen, nutrients and organic
carbon, and particulate material such as pollen, larvae,
